# .envrc.example â€” copy to .envrc in your project, edit, then run: direnv allow
#
# When you cd into a directory with .envrc, direnv runs it and sets env / tools
# per directory (Node version, Python venv, API keys, etc.). The real .envrc
# is usually not committed (secrets, machine-specific paths). This file is a
# template so others (or you on a new machine) know what to put in .envrc.

# Use a Node version (mise)
# use node

# Use a Python version (mise)
# use python

# Or pin exact versions (mise creates .tool-versions)
# use node@20
# use python@3.12

# Export env vars (replace with real values in .envrc)
# export API_URL=https://api.example.com
# export API_KEY=your_key_here

# Load a .env file (if you use one)
# dotenv
